## Plan: Add `mistral-instruct-v3` Handler

**Only one file changes: `common/chat.cpp`**

### What to add

**Step 1 — New handler function** (insert at line 1518, between the closing `}` of `common_chat_params_init_gigachat_v3` and `namespace workaround {`):

```cpp
static common_chat_params common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(
        const common_chat_template &          tmpl,
        const autoparser::generation_params & inputs) {
    common_chat_params data;

    // Renders [INST]…[/INST] user turns, system prepended to first user turn,
    // </s> after each assistant turn — all done by the jinja template.
    data.prompt = common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl(tmpl, inputs);
    data.format = COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_PEG_NATIVE;

    auto parser = build_chat_peg_parser([&](common_chat_peg_builder & p) {
        return p.literal(inputs.generation_prompt) + p.content(p.rest());
    });

    data.parser = parser.save();
    return data;
}
```

**Step 2 — Detection block** (insert at the end of `common_chat_try_specialized_template`, before `return std::nullopt`):

```cpp
    // Mistral Instruct v0.3 — [INST]/[/INST] format; no [SYSTEM_PROMPT] (unlike Ministral 3)
    if (src.find("[INST]")          != std::string::npos &&
        src.find("[/INST]")         != std::string::npos &&
        src.find("[SYSTEM_PROMPT]") == std::string::npos) {
        LOG_DBG("Using specialized template: mistral-instruct-v3\n");
        return common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(tmpl, params);
    }
```

### Key design choices
- **`common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl`** is reused (same as every other handler) — the jinja template already encodes the v0.3 formatting rules.
- **Content-only PEG parser** — v0.3 has no structured tool-call output tokens requiring constrained decoding.
- **Detection order** — placed last so all more-specific handlers run first; Ministral 3's `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` check at line 1640 prevents any overlap.
- **No header changes** — the new function is `static`, purely internal.

